---
title: Apricot Balsamic Glazed Pork Filet with Ginger Garlic Rice & Sesame Green Beans
description: A glaze you’re be thinking about for days! Apricot jam meets balsamic vinegar for a sweet, sticky, and tangy sauce for savory pork filet. Don’t sleep on the sides because they get lots of flavor love, too: jasmine rice cooked with ginger, garlic, and stock, plus steamed green beans that get a nutty aroma from sesame oil. Drizzle everything with some soy sauce for some serious umami satisfaction.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/668c3529012d858ae3811307-7095b3c6.jpeg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/668c3529012d858ae3811307-en-US.pdf
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/apricot-balsamic-glazed-pork-filet-668c3529012d858ae3811307
servings: 2
course: main course
cuisine: North America
time required: 45 minutes
author: Sara Heilman
nutrition:
  calories: 770 kcal
  fat: 37 g
  saturated fat: 15 g
  carbohydrates: 68 g
  sugar: 21 g
  protein: 33 g
  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 1710 mg
---

Wash and dry produce (except green beans).

Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Halve, peel, and mince half the @shallot{1} (whole shallot for 4 servings).

== Ginger Garlic Rice ==

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add ginger, scallion whites, and half the garlic (all for 4 servings); cook until softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, half the @chicken stock concentrate{1/2%unit} (you'll use the rest later) and @water{3/4%cup} (1 1/2 cups for 4). Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

== Pork and Glaze ==

Pat @pork filet{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and @fry seasoning{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4 servings; we sent more).

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add pork and cook, turning occasionally, until browned and cooked through, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145º.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest. Wash out pan.

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add minced shallot and cook until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @apricot jam{1%unit} and @balsamic vinegar{5%tsp}; simmer until syrupy, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Stir in @water{1/4%cup} (1/2 cup for 4 servings), remaining stock concentrate, and @sugar{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4). Bring to a boil, then lower heat; simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Remove from heat. Stir in @butter{1%tbsp} until melted. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

== Sesame Green Beans ==

Pierce @green beans{6%oz} bag with a #fork{}; place bag on a #plate{}. Microwave until tender, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: No microwave? No problem! Steam beans in a small pot with a splash of water until just tender, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Carefully transfer green beans to a #medium bowl{}. Toss with @sesame oil{1%tbsp} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

== To Serve ==

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir any resting juices from pork into pan with glaze.

Slice pork crosswise.

Divide rice, pork, and green beans between plates. Drizzle pork with glaze. Top everything with scallion greens and @soy sauce{2%tbsp} to taste. Serve.